    <section>
      <title>Section 4.2:
        The Inverse of a Matrix (MX2) </title>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.1 (~5 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a2s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-b-a-a">
    Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a2s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-b-a-a-a">A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \end{array}\right]</m>.
    Find a <m original-id="MX2-s3a2s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-b-a-a-b">3 \times 3</m> matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3a2s1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-b-a-a-c">B</m> such that <m original-id="MX2-s3a2s1p1m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-b-a-a-d">BA=A</m>, that is,
    <me original-id="MX2-s3a2s1p1m5" internal-id="me-MX2-c-b-a-a-e">
      \left[\begin{array}{ccc} \unknown &amp; \unknown &amp; \unknown \\ 
      \unknown &amp; \unknown &amp; \unknown 
      \\ \unknown &amp; \unknown &amp; \unknown \end{array}\right]
      \left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \end{array}\right]
    =
      \left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \end{array}\right]
    </me>
    Check your guess using technology.
        </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Definition 4.2.1 </title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-d-a-a">
    The identity matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-d-a-a-a">I_n</m> (or just <m original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-d-a-a-b">I</m> when <m original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-d-a-a-c">n</m> is obvious from context) is
    the <m original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-d-a-a-d">n \times n</m> matrix
    <me original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1m5" internal-id="me-MX2-c-d-a-a-e">I_n = \left[\begin{array}{cccc} 1 &amp; 0  &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots  \\
    \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \ddots &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \end{array}\right].</me>
    It has a <m original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1m6" internal-id="m-MX2-c-d-a-a-f">1</m> on each diagonal element and a <m original-id="MX2-s3d4s1p1m7" internal-id="m-MX2-c-d-a-a-g">0</m> in every other position.
            </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Fact 4.2.2 </title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3f5s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-e-a-a">
      For any square matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3f5s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-e-a-a-a">A</m>, <m original-id="MX2-s3f5s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-e-a-a-b">IA=AI=A</m>:
      <me original-id="MX2-s3f5s1p1m3" internal-id="me-MX2-c-e-a-a-c">
        \left[\begin{array}{ccc} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \end{array}\right]
        \left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \end{array}\right]
      =
        \left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \end{array}\right]
          \left[\begin{array}{ccc} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \end{array}\right]
      =
        \left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \end{array}\right]
      </me>
            </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.2 (~15 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-a">
Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-a-a">T: \IR^n \rightarrow \IR^m</m> be a linear map with standard matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-a-b">A</m>.
Sort the following items into three groups of statements: a group that means
<m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-a-c">T</m> is <em original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1e4" internal-id="em-MX2-c-f-a-a-d">injective</em>, a group that means <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1m5" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-a-e">T</m> is <em original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1e6" internal-id="em-MX2-c-f-a-a-f">surjective</em>,
and a group that means <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1m7" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-a-g">T</m> is <em original-id="MX2-s3a6s1p1e8" internal-id="em-MX2-c-f-a-a-h">bijective</em>.
        </p>
        <ol marker="A." original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2" internal-id="ol-MX2-c-f-a-b">
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l1" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-a">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-a-a"> <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-a-a-a">A\vec x=\vec b</m> has a solution for all <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-a-a-b">\vec b\in\IR^m</m>
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l2" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-b">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l2p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-b-a"> <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l2p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-b-a-a">A\vec x=\vec b</m> has a unique solution for all <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l2p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-b-a-b">\vec b\in\IR^m</m>
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l3" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-c">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l3p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-c-a"> <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l3p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-c-a-a">A\vec x=\vec 0</m> has a unique solution.
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l4" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-d">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l4p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-d-a"> The columns of <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l4p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-d-a-a">A</m> span <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l4p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-d-a-b">\IR^m</m>
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l5" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-e">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l5p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-e-a"> The columns of <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l5p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-e-a-a">A</m> are linearly independent
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l6" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-f">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l6p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-f-a"> The columns of <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l6p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-f-a-a">A</m> are a basis of <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l6p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-f-a-b">\IR^m</m>
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l7" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-g">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l7p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-g-a"> Every column of <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l7p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-g-a-a">\RREF(A)</m> has a pivot
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l8" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-h">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l8p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-h-a"> Every row of <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l8p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-h-a-a">\RREF(A)</m> has a pivot
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l9" internal-id="li-MX2-c-f-a-b-i">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l9p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-f-a-b-i-a"> <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l9p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-i-a-a">m=n</m> and <m original-id="MX2-s3a6s1o2l9p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-f-a-b-i-a-b">\RREF(A)=I</m>
</p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.3 (~5 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-g-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-g-a-a-a">T: \IR^3 \rightarrow \IR^3</m> be the linear transformation given by the standard matrix
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-g-a-a-b">A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\ 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p2" internal-id="p-MX2-c-g-a-b">
  Write an augmented matrix representing the system of equations given by <m original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p2m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-g-a-b-a">T(\vec x)=\vec{0}</m>,
  that is, <m original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p2m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-g-a-b-b">A\vec x=\left[\begin{array}{c}0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]</m>.
  Then solve <m original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p2m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-g-a-b-c">T(\vec x)=\vec{0}</m> to find the kernel of <m original-id="MX2-s3a7s1p2m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-g-a-b-d">T</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Definition 4.2.3 </title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3d9s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-i-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-a-a">T: \IR^n \rightarrow \IR^n</m> be a linear map with standard matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-a-b">A</m>.
    </p>
        <ul original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2" internal-id="ul-MX2-c-i-a-b">
          <li original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l1" internal-id="li-MX2-c-i-a-b-a">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-i-a-b-a-a">  If <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-a-a-a">T</m> is a bijection and <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-a-a-b">\vec b</m> is any <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-a-a-c">\IR^n</m> vector, 
  then <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l1p1m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-a-a-d">T(\vec x)=A\vec x=\vec b</m> has a unique solution.
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l2" internal-id="li-MX2-c-i-a-b-b">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l2p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-i-a-b-b-a"> So we may define an <term original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l2p1t1" internal-id="term-MX2-c-i-a-b-b-a-a">inverse map</term><idx original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l2p1i2" internal-id="idx-MX2-c-i-a-b-b-a-b">inverse map</idx> <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l2p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-b-a-c">T^{-1} : \IR^n \rightarrow \IR^n</m> 
  by setting <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l2p1m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-b-a-d">T^{-1}(\vec b)</m> to be this unique solution.
</p>
          </li>
          <li original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3" internal-id="li-MX2-c-i-a-b-c">
            <p original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a"> Let <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-a">A^{-1}</m> be the standard matrix for <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-b">T^{-1}</m>. We call <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-c">A^{-1}</m> the
<term original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1t4" internal-id="term-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-d">inverse matrix</term><idx original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1i5" internal-id="idx-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-e">inverse matrix</idx> of <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1m6" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-f">A</m>, so we also say that <m original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1m7" internal-id="m-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-g">A</m> is <term original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1t8" internal-id="term-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-h">invertible</term><idx original-id="MX2-s3d9s1u2l3p1i9" internal-id="idx-MX2-c-i-a-b-c-a-i">invertible</idx>.
</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.4 (~20 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-a">T: \IR^3 \rightarrow \IR^3</m> be the linear transformation given by the standard matrix
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-b">A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; -1 &amp; -6 \\ 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Part 1.</em>
        </p>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10t2p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-b-a">
  Write an augmented matrix representing the system of equations given by <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t2p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-b-a-a">T(\vec x)=\vec{e}_1</m>,
  that is, <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t2p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-b-a-b">A\vec x=\left[\begin{array}{c}1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]</m>.
  Then solve <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t2p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-b-a-c">T(\vec x)=\vec{e}_1</m> to find <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t2p1m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-b-a-d">T^{-1}(\vec{e}_1)</m>.
      </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.4 (~20 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-a">T: \IR^3 \rightarrow \IR^3</m> be the linear transformation given by the standard matrix
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-b">A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; -1 &amp; -6 \\ 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Part 2.</em>
        </p>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10t3p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-c-a">
   Solve <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t3p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-c-a-a">T(\vec x)=\vec{e}_2</m> to find <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t3p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-c-a-b">T^{-1}(\vec{e}_2)</m>.
      </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.4 (~20 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-a">T: \IR^3 \rightarrow \IR^3</m> be the linear transformation given by the standard matrix
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-b">A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; -1 &amp; -6 \\ 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Part 3.</em>
        </p>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10t4p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-d-a">
   Solve <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t4p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-d-a-a">T(\vec x)=\vec{e}_3</m> to find <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t4p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-d-a-b">T^{-1}(\vec{e}_3)</m>.
      </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.4 (~20 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-a">T: \IR^3 \rightarrow \IR^3</m> be the linear transformation given by the standard matrix
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a10i1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-a-a-b">A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 2 &amp; -1 &amp; -6 \\ 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Part 4.</em>
        </p>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a10t5p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-j-e-a">
   Write <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t5p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-e-a-a">A^{-1}</m>, the standard matrix for <m original-id="MX2-s3a10t5p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-j-e-a-b">T^{-1}</m>.
      </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Observation 4.2.4 </title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3o12s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-l-a-a">
We could have solved these three systems simultaneously
by row reducing the matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3o12s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-l-a-a-a">[A\,|\,I]</m> at once.
<me original-id="MX2-s3o12s1p1m2" internal-id="me-MX2-c-l-a-a-b">
  \left[\begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
    2 &amp; -1 &amp; -6 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
    2 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
    1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
  \end{array}\right] \sim
  \left[\begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
    1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; -2 &amp; 3 \\
    0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; -5 &amp; 14 &amp; -18 \\
    0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -3 &amp; 4
  \end{array}\right]
</me>
        </p>
