      <slide>
        <title>Observation 4.2.5 </title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3o17s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-q-a-a">
    An <m original-id="MX2-s3o17s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-q-a-a-a">n\times n</m> matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3o17s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-q-a-a-b">A</m> is invertible if and only if <m original-id="MX2-s3o17s1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-q-a-a-c">\RREF(A) = I_n</m>.
    </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.7 (~10 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-r-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-a-a-a">T:\IR^2\to\IR^2</m> be the bijective linear map defined by
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-a-a-b">T\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}x\\y\end{array}\right]\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c} 2x -3y \\ -3x + 5y\end{array}\right]</m>,
  with the inverse map
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-a-a-c">T^{-1}\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}x\\y\end{array}\right]\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c} 5x+ 3y \\ 3x + 2y\end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Part 1.</em>
        </p>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a18t2p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-r-b-a">
    Compute <m original-id="MX2-s3a18t2p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-b-a-a">(T^{-1}\circ T)\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}-2\\1\end{array}\right]\right)</m>.
      </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Activity 4.2.7 (~10 min)</title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-r-a-a">
  Let <m original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-a-a-a">T:\IR^2\to\IR^2</m> be the bijective linear map defined by
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-a-a-b">T\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}x\\y\end{array}\right]\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c} 2x -3y \\ -3x + 5y\end{array}\right]</m>,
  with the inverse map
  <m original-id="MX2-s3a18i1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-a-a-c">T^{-1}\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}x\\y\end{array}\right]\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c} 5x+ 3y \\ 3x + 2y\end{array}\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Part 2.</em>
        </p>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3a18t3p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-r-c-a">
    If <m original-id="MX2-s3a18t3p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-c-a-a">A</m> is the standard matrix for <m original-id="MX2-s3a18t3p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-c-a-b">T</m> and <m original-id="MX2-s3a18t3p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-c-a-c">A^{-1}</m> is the
    standard matrix for <m original-id="MX2-s3a18t3p1m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-c-a-d">T^{-1}</m>, find the <m original-id="MX2-s3a18t3p1m5" internal-id="m-MX2-c-r-c-a-e">2\times 2</m> matrix 
    <me original-id="MX2-s3a18t3p1m6" internal-id="me-MX2-c-r-c-a-f">A^{-1}A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}\unknown&amp;\unknown\\\unknown&amp;\unknown\end{array}\right].</me>
      </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Observation 4.2.6 </title>
        <p original-id="MX2-s3o19s1p1" internal-id="p-MX2-c-s-a-a">
  <m original-id="MX2-s3o19s1p1m1" internal-id="m-MX2-c-s-a-a-a">T^{-1}\circ T=T\circ T^{-1}</m> is the identity map for any bijective
  linear transformation <m original-id="MX2-s3o19s1p1m2" internal-id="m-MX2-c-s-a-a-b">T</m>. Therefore
  <m original-id="MX2-s3o19s1p1m3" internal-id="m-MX2-c-s-a-a-c">A^{-1}A=AA^{-1}</m> equals the identity matrix <m original-id="MX2-s3o19s1p1m4" internal-id="m-MX2-c-s-a-a-d">I</m> for any invertible matrix
  <m original-id="MX2-s3o19s1p1m5" internal-id="m-MX2-c-s-a-a-e">A</m>.
        </p>
